description.text:
I know, it is not a beauty. It is just an easy way to enlarge the boat
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:272132
to make it big enough to carry the strong and heavy outrunner motor which I use for my airplane
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:86982
I simply printed a 100 mm extension and daubed it between bow and stern part - with tape as usual ;-)
At first I tried a 35 mm surface propeller which I got from a friend. This Propeller is more effective than my printed propeller. It needs less motor speed and was hardly to control because it pushes strong even with little throttle. So later I preferred the printed propeller. It is not so wild and makes more noise due to the higher motor speed ;-).
With increasing speed, the bow shoots up and throws a large bow wave which easily can splash water into the boat. To hold the bow low it was necessary to shift the weight forward. In the end even as much as possible. Sorry for the bad video quality.
I uploaded it twice with different size but it doesn't make any difference. Partly it is highly compressed.
http://youtu.be/WXiN_QXZCPc BTW, the ducks were not impressed at all...

Printing
The best is, if you print it with spiral vase methode. Then you will get a neat surface without any noses from layer change.
The hull is 3.0 mm thick.
I printed with layer hight: 0.3 mm and width: 0.6 mm.
Anyway, you have to print it hollow with one perimeter otherwise it will not fit inside the interface part. Interfaces
The interfaces are supposed to put them fifty-fifty in the gap of each hull part. In this way the the hull parts are aligned and easy to glue.
Before gluing you should mask the edges of the hulls with tape to keep them clean from glue. Drive
It is designed for the Roxxy BL-Outrunner http://www.robbe.de/roxxy-bl-outrunner-2834-08.html
Driving shaft:
3 mm rod 130 mm long with 11 mm M3 thread on one end. Coupling
3 heat shrink tubes, one into each other, both about 50 mm long.
I fastened the second one with rubber band to the motor shaft before shrinking the bigger one upon it. It is not necessary on the other side because of the longer contact surface. Surface Propeller
This propeller needs an adapter from M4 to M3. Additional it had to be shortened to fit between the rudder and the stern. Rudder Mount
The rudder mount now is 2.5 mm longer. All remaing parts you can take from: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:272132

comments.text: Did you have to put any kind of seal in the drive shaft tube to keep water from coming up into the boat? I've got all the electronics required, I'd like to try to make one of these.
comments.author: jam4ar

comments.text:
No, I just decently greased the tube and the shaft before I put the shaft into the tube.
This should be enough if the tube fits good to the shaft.

title: Makerbot/Flashforge filament feed upgrade (prevent motor jam)

description.text:
Mk2 is now here, download from my page! Ever had to repeatedly un-jam flexi-filament from your MakerBot or FlashForge 3Dprinter? Now you wont have to with this easy but effective upgrade.
All you have to do is replace one component with this new upgrade and motor jamming will be a thing of the past. Jamming my still occur occasional but the motor will not, helping to protect your motor from damage. Un-jamming is consequently much easier and can even be achieved by using the 'change filament' - 'unload' program on your 3D printer. Unscrewing fiddly nuts and bots is now a thing of the past. Print time @ 0.15mm is 15mins. Any comments are welcome. Thanks :),
ReneeCel

title: Yet another filament spool holder - Modular

description.text:
This spool holder has module-based supports that allow various spool height depending on the number of modules.
The horizontal length is fixed (8.5 cm), but I intend to provide a modular solution as well, as soon as I find a suitable way to support the spool weight (do not hesitate to provide suggestions in comments). I designed it to use less than 10cm parts, so that my PrintrBot simple can print it.

Print two support bases and support tops, and as much support extenders as needed.
Engage the supports parts one above another. You'll probably need a small hammer, a rubber hammer would be perfect. Be careful not to break the pins in this operation. Finally, print one bar, put on your spool and engage the bar in the support. I designed it so that no printing material will be needed. FreeCAD sources are provided in the 7-zip archive.

author: erossman

description.text: Treball Expressió Plàstica novè Lliurement

Here is a bowling ball stance I made for someone, I have uploaded a blank one for anyone else who would like this. I removed most of the material so not to waste any plastic  but still ensuring it has its strengths. I have also smoothed off all corners so there should be no sharp edges.
Just print!

comments.text: Very nice design. I've made several. On two of them I bumped up the scaling in Cura by 12% in all directions to fit inside a pocket in the bottom of a bowling bag. Worked great, still left a small amount of clearance under the ball when resting on a flat surface.
comments.author: rickthing123

comments.text: Great to see that this still worked great after scaling the model up slightly.
